I reread the question and see that a fair use ruling is irrelevant to the question. It seems very likely that the court will affirm that the Java API is protected under the copyright act.
Based on comments during oral arguments, most justices were sympathetic to Oracles claim.

From the Economist 
“America’s Supreme Court will hear a case today that could have a huge impact on the future of software. The plaintiff, Oracle, alleges that Google infringed its copyright when it reimplemented Java, a popular programming language that Oracle owns, more than ten years ago. Google has warned that a ruling in Oracle’s favour would limit competition and innovation in the software industry: firms would no longer be able just to copy the interfaces that allow rival programs to work together but would have to ask for permission and pay a fee, creating all kinds of headaches and introducing friction in the industry. Other big tech firms, such as IBM and Microsoft, tend to agree—those two filed briefs in support of Alphabet, Google’s parent company. Oracle’s own history should make it realise that limited copying is good for innovation. It got its start by adopting SQL, a computer language to query databases developed by IBM.“
This case given the 4 -4 conservative to liberal balance in the court could end up a 4-4 case, thus it would not be the law of the land that Oracle would win and gain this copy write protection.

Two questions before the Court: (1) Does copyright protection extend to a software interface? (2) If so, does the  use of a software interface in the context of creating a new computer program constitute fair use? The question says that it does not turn on the second question and I see very little chance of the Court ruling No to question 1 especially as the Court moves further to the political right and it becomes publicly increasingly popular to scrutinise the big names of tech.

The fair use proviso is very important here and an odd way of asking the question that will likely lead to answers to a different question (I feel I am guessing a little what the question is as to say fair use is immaterial is not at all clear, the phrasing should say this resolves on copyright only, or copyright and fair use together).  The jury decision that was in googles favour and overturned was based on fair use not copyright. On this basis the most likely outcome seems to be yes to copyright and yes to fair use (say 50%), then maybe 25% chance either way as for copyright itself, and so a 75% chance on copyright itself.

For that reason, you cannot receive copyright protection, perhaps patent protection, but not copyright protection. " Even Oracle has copied code from the Amazon S3 API for compatibility with Amazon systems. We also have that in case of being subject to copyright, Google argues that it can make use of this code due to the fair use policy, which encourages and allows the development of new ideas based on previous ideas, and counterbalances those Copyright.
